{"id":14881373,"mediaExerciseId":"2da93770-5943-490f-8bcc-7a7ef3f229bb","exerciseName":"2","chapterName":"12","chapterTitle":"Some Lessons From Capital Market History","groupId":612365,"groupTitle":"Minicase Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":419,"solutions":[{"id":6249764,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this problem, we will define what EAR is and how it can help in planning for the appropriate action in investing. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"The EAR or effective annual rate is the annual rate without the consideration of inflation. This is similar to the nominal rate of return that was discussed in previous exercises. \n\nthe effective annual rate is important to understand since this is how we can compare the different investment options. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"Since in this case, you will receive the full $5\\%$ match, then the EAR is $100\\%$ since the amount you invested is the same amount that will be given back to you. \n\nHowever, since it is only the nominal rate, then the percentage will still vary if inflation is taken into consideration. Therefore, it is not always a good idea to match the plan since it does not provide room for adjustment based on the inflation rate and the behavior of the market. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"83fa7f0c-0471-4706-b3b7-26dbdb01c57f","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":3}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","im